<h1><b>&nbsp; SPIDER &amp; WEB</b></h1>
d27 7
a33 2
 <a name="AVAILABLE"></a>
 <h3>SYSTEM AVAILABILITY</h3>
d35 2
a36 22
<p>
The SPIDER distribution consists of two separate modules, SPIDER
and Web. The SPIDER module is written in FORTRAN and is used for
mathematical manipulation of images and their contents. The Web
module is written in <i>C</i> or in <i>Java</i> 
and is used for visual display and
interaction with images created by the SPIDER module or to be used
by SPIDER. SPIDER/Web workstation with at
least 128 Mb of memory. You should have at least 10 Gb of disk
space for your images. </p>

<p>Recompilation and linking of SPIDER requires a FORTRAN 90
compiler.  We currently use a PGI compiler on Linux, SGI
compilers for Altix and Irix, and IBM compilers for AIX. 
Recompilation and linking of Xwindow WEB requires a <i>C</i>
compiler and Motif/X-Window libraries on your computer.
The standard <i>gcc</i> works well. </p>

<p>We can provide SPIDER/Web for Irix and GNU-Linux. We no longer
provide the Windows or Compaq (DEC) Unix versions.</p>

<p>We regularly run SPIDER/Web on various platforms including: 
d41 1
a41 1
Our current preferred platform is a Dual Core Dual Opteron based
d43 2
a44 1
on a cluster of these machines.</p>  
d46 36
a81 1
<p></p>
d83 13
a95 55
<h3>DISTRIBUTION</h3>

<p><strong>On Linux, and other Unix machines:</strong> The modules 
contain sample Makefiles for compiling on various GNU-Linux architectures 
and for IBM SP3 systems running AIX. 
We provide executables targeted for: AMD 32 and 64 bit platforms,
Intel 32 bit platforms, and SGI Itanium platforms.

It is possible that one of the SPIDER/Web executables which we supply
will work on your machines.  However the FORTRAN and C code
which we supply, may have to be recompiled and linked for use on some
machines. Such compilation will require familiarity with the local
operating system to set the necessary compilation/linking flags and
libraries. Please understand that due to limited staff and
equipment we may not be able to assist with problems you encounter
running SPIDER/Web on machines other than those listed above.</p>

<p><strong>On SGI Irix:</strong> The UNIX SPIDER and Web modules contain
executable versions of SPIDER for use on SGI workstations running
Irix 6.0+ The modules also contain all source code, object
libraries, and makefiles needed for module generation. It is
probable that one of the supplied executables will work fine and
you will not need to recompile.</p> 


<p></p>

<p><strong>Media:</strong> Downloadable from the Internet</p>

<p></p>

<h3>IMAGE DISPLAY WITHOUT WEB</h3>

<p>It is possible to view images from SPIDER on most workstations
without using Web. You could write your own software to do this
using Web as a model. Alternatively you might use the <a href=
"man/cptoraw.html">"CP TO RAW"</a> command in SPIDER to convert a
SPIDER format image to a 8-bit "raw" image. Most modern 
workstations (including SUN) have a native graphics
command for display of such images or conversion of such images
into their own format. If you choose to go that route, you can deal
with basic display functions <em>but cannot easily emulate many
interactive functions such as interactive windowing contained
within Web</em>.</p> 

<p></p>

<h3>WWW site</h3>

<p>The latest SPIDER/WEB information is available on at:
<a href= "http://www.wadsworth.org/spider_doc">http://www.wadsworth.org/spider_doc</a></p>

<p></p>

<h3>ENQUIRIES</h3>
