<h1><strong> &nbsp; SPID<sub>E</sub>R & W<sub>E</sub>B</strong></h1>
d15 1
a15 2
<a name="AVAILABLE"> 

d18 78
a95 70
The SPIDER distribution consists of two separate modules, SPIDER and
Web. The SPIDER module is written in FORTRAN and is used for
mathematical manipulation of images and their contents.  The Web module
is written in <I>C</I> and is used for visual display and interaction
with images created by the SPIDER module or to be used by SPIDER.
SPIDER/Web requires an 8 bit color workstation with at least 128 Mb of
memory.  You should have at least 10 Gb of disk space
for your images. <p>

Recompilation and linking of SPIDER requires a FORTRAN 90 compiler.
Recompilation and linking of WEB requires a <I>C</I> compiler and
Motif/X-Window libraries on your computer.<p>

We can provide SPIDER/Web for Irix and GNU-Linux.  We no longer provide 
the Windows or Compaq (DEC) Unix versions.<p>

<li><h3>DISTRIBUTION</h3>

   <strong>On SGI:</strong> The UNIX SPIDER and Web modules contain executable 
   versions of SPIDER for use on SGI workstations running Irix 6.0+  The modules 
   also contain all source code, object libraries, and makefiles needed for module 
   generation. It is probable that one of the supplied executables will work fine and
   you will not need to recompile.
   <p>

   <strong>On Linux, and other Unix machines:</strong> The modules contain sample 
   Makefiles,  object libraries, and sample executables for use on 
   various GNU-Linux architectures and for IBM_SP3.  It is possible that one of the
   SPIDER/Web executables which we supply will work on your implementations, 
   however, the FORTRAN and C code which we supply 
   may have to be recompiled and linked on those machines.  Such 
   compilation will require familiarity with the local operating system 
   to set the necessary compilation/linking flags and libraries.  
   Please understand that due to limited staff and equipment we may 
   not be able to assist with problems you encounter running SPIDER/Web 
   on non-SGI machines.
   <p>

   <p>
   <strong>Media:</strong> CDROM or ftp transfer <p>



</ul> 
<li><h3>IMAGE DISPLAY WITHOUT WEB</h3>
   It is possible to view images from SPIDER on most workstations 
   without using Web.  You could write your own software to  
   do this using Web as a model.  Alternatively you might use the 
   <a href="man/cptoraw.html">"CP TO RAW"</a>
   command in SPIDER to convert a SPIDER format image to a 8-bit "raw" 
   image.  Most 8-bit color or black-and-white workstations (including 
   SUN) have a native graphics command for display of such images or 
   conversion of such images into their own format.  If you choose to go 
   that route, you can deal with basic display functions <em>but cannot
   easily emulate many interactive functions such as interactive 
   windowing contained within Web</em>.
   <p>

<li><h3>WWW  site</h3>
    The latest SPIDER/WEB information is available on the internet at: 
    <a href="http://www.wadsworth.org/spider_doc"> 
      http://www.wadsworth.org/spider_doc</a>
    <p>

<li><h3>ENQUIRIES</h3>
    Joachim Frank                                        <br>
    Wadsworth Labs, P.O. Box 509, Albany, New York 12201 <br>
    phone: 518-474-7002                                  <br>
    fax:   518-486-2191                                  <br>
    email:  <a href= "mailto:joachim@@wadsworth.org">joachim@@wadsworth.org</a>
