<H1><STRONG> &nbsp; SPID<SUB>E</SUB>R & W<SUB>E</SUB>B</STRONG></H1>
d13 2
a14 2
<HR>
<A NAME="AVAILABLE"> <H2>SYSTEM AVAILABILITY</H2>
d16 2
d23 26
a48 31
SPIDER/Web requires an 8 bit color workstation with at least 64 Mb of
memory.  You should have at least 6 Gb of disk space
for your images. <P>

Recompilation and linking of SPIDER requires a FORTRAN 90 compiler while
recompilation and linking of WEB requires a <I>C</I> compiler and
Motif/X-Window libraries on your computer. <P>

 We can provide SPIDER/Web for either UNIX or Intel NT.    The
software has been developed and tested on SGI workstations.  A few sites
are running it on Compaq (DEC) Unix workstations and one site has some
experience on SUN workstations, but at this time we still advise
running it on SGI systems. The NT version is newly released and is only
in use at a few external sites so far.<P>


<LI><H3>DISTRIBUTION</H3>

   <STRONG>On SGI:</STRONG> The UNIX SPIDER and Web modules contain executable versions of SPIDER for 
   use on SGI workstations running Irix 6.0+ and on Compaq (Dec) for
   Unix 4.0+   The modules also contain all source code, object libraries, 
   and makefiles needed for module generation. 
   <P>

   <STRONG>On  Sun, Linux, and other Unix machines:</STRONG> The modules contain sample 
   Makefiles,  object libraries, and executables for use on 
   IBM_SP3, and Sun Sparc-Stations.  The modules were targeted at 
   SGI workstations and have not been extensively tested on non-SGI 
   workstations.  It is probable that SPIDER/Web will work on non-SGI
   Unix implementations, however, the FORTRAN and C code which we supply 
   will have to be recompiled and linked on those machines.  Such 
d52 6
a57 18
   not be able to assist with problems you encounter porting SPIDER/Web 
   to non-SGI machines.
   <P>

   <STRONG>On NT:</STRONG> The SPIDER module contains a sample
   Makefile,  object library, and executable for use on Intel NT 4.0. 
   (Recently one site has used this on Windows 2000 also.)  
   SPIDER has not been extensively tested on NT.  We are able to 
   provide an Intel NT  version of Web that requires Run-time-libraries from
   <I> Nutcracker </I> for
   conversion of the X-Window calls to Windows NT equivalents.  Each
   run-time library copy costs us $150.  Thus, we only distribute Web
   for NT to labs expessing a desire to use it.   At a future date we
   hope to provide a Java implementation of Web taht will run on both 
   Unix and NT platforms. 
 
   <P>
   <STRONG>Media:</STRONG> CDROM or ftp transfer <P>
